recommandationVideos.Title: Female Ukraine combat medic fires back as four Russian tanks attack her trench and wound comrades
recommandationVideos.Description:
Female Ukraine combat medic fires back as four Russian tanks attack her trench and wound comrades. Intense first-person footage revealed the brutal reality of trench-fighting in Ukraine. The video was taken by a female solider of the 47th Brigade fighting in Avdiivka. Troops can be seen fighting near a trench as bullets whistle overhead. Heavy machine gun fire tears through trees and grenades are hurled above ground. The fighting continues under the cover of the dark until dawn. Because the trench is so narrow, they‚Äôre forced to fight in a long single-file line. Russian soldiers attack with shells and heavy artillery injuring some squad members. The female soldier uses tuff-cut scissors and medication to patch-up wounded troops. An incoming tank opens fire on their trench and the squad are forced to retreat. Hoping not to be spotted by the Russians, they lay low and hide in their trench. As the tank approaches, the wounded soldier hands over an anti-tank missile, then a panic breaks out and the squad brace themselves for impact. Luckily, the Russians don‚Äôt see them and continue roaming the battlefield. A few moments later, they look overhead to make sure the coast is clear. The female soldier helps her comrade to safety, and they run through the forest. Russian bullets fall around them as they jump into an armoured vehicle. Under heavy attack, bullets ping off the vehicle as they make their escape. They arrive at a medical facility, where the man receives urgent treatment. A narrow escape for the squad, they look relieved.

The United States has said it does not seek a war with Iran but will ‚Äúprotect itself‚Äù and ‚Äúrespond appropriately‚Äù following a drone attack by an Iran-backed group killed three US soldiers and wounded dozens more in Jordan.

The group behind the attack is called Islamic Resistance in Iraq.   They are part of an Iranian-sponsored network across the Middle East known as the Axis of Resistance.

The Niobium radar, a product of the Nizhny Novgorod Research Institute of Radio Engineering, traces its lineage back to the Sky family of radar systems. The development journey began in the 1980s with the creation of the Sky complex. Over the years, this family saw notable advancements with improved modifications such as Nebo-U in the post-Soviet era.
In 2013, a significant stride occurred with the introduction of the Niobium radar, representing a pinnacle in this lineage. Building on the legacy of its predecessors, Niobium emerged as a state-of-the-art radar system, incorporating advanced features and capabilities. The radar's development was marked by rigorous testing and trial operations, ensuring its efficacy in real-world scenarios.
The Ministry of Defense's decision to initiate serial production in 2017 marked a pivotal milestone, signifying confidence in the radar's performance. Since then, ongoing deliveries to the Aerospace Forces and ground forces have facilitated the integration of Niobium radars into Russia's defense infrastructure. This evolutionary journey underscores a commitment to staying at the forefront of technological advancements in air defense.

recommandationVideos.Title: Why is the Kh-22 the Real Beast in Russia's Missile Arsenal?
recommandationVideos.Description:
Since the start of the conflict in Ukraine, the specter of Russian missile attacks has loomed large. While hypersonic missiles like the Kinzhal grab headlines, it is the Kh-22, a seemingly less glamorous behemoth, that has Ukrainian air defenses truly worried. 

Back in 2000, Ukraine handed over 386 Kh-22 missiles to Russia as part of a repayment for gas debt. Throughout the full-scale invasion, Russian forces have launched approximately 300 Kh-22 missiles at Ukraine, and up until now, none of these missiles have been intercepted or brought down by Ukrainian air defense forces. The Ukrainian air force spokesperson, Yuriy Ignat, openly admitted this fact, emphasizing the serious danger posed by Kh-22 missiles to Ukraine.

In its coverage last December, Moscow's media TASS reported that Ignat highlighted the technical hurdles posed by the Kh-22 missile, underlining the need for specialized means of interception. The missile's speed and trajectory pose a significant challenge for traditional air defense systems. 

Ignat specifically noted the Patriot air defense systems as potentially effective against the Kh-22, but their success in the Ukrainian context remains uncertain. Despite receiving Western support in the form of SAMP-T, Patriot, Iris-T, NASAMS, and Crotale air defense systems, Ukrainian authorities argue that the provided systems are inadequate to counter the Kh-22 threat. 

What makes this missile particularly challenging to defeat, and why this cold war relic gives Ukraine more chills than the hypersonic Kinzhal?

As of July 2023, it is uncertain whether Armata tanks have started participating in direct combat. There are several potential reasons for their non-involvement so far. The exact number of T-14 tanks operated by Russia remains unclear. Various news reports suggest that the Kremlin initially placed orders for several thousand T-14 Armatas to be produced several years ago, but the timeline for their arrival appears uncertain and may have been extended beyond 2025. recommandationVideos.Description:
Joint press conference by the NATO Secretary General, Jens Stoltenberg and the US Secretary of State,  Antony J. Blinken, 29 January 2024.

üó£ | NATO Secretary General:

Thanks so much, Secretary Blinken, dear Tony,
Thank you for hosting me here in Washington.

It is always good to meet with you.
And even more important given the dangers we face.

So let me begin by offering my deepest condolences for the US troops killed and wounded in yesterday‚Äôs drone attack in Jordan.

We see Iran continue to destabilise the region.

Iran also bears responsibility for backing terrorists who attack our ships in the Red Sea.

Tehran‚Äôs behaviour reminds us of what a world without rules looks like:
Unpredictable and dangerous.
A world where our security becomes more expensive.

I welcome your tireless diplomacy, Secretary Blinken, to prevent further escalation of the war in Gaza. 
Your efforts to alleviate human suffering.
And your hard work toward a peaceful resolution.

Russia‚Äôs brutal war against Ukraine is nearing the two-year mark.
And a Russian victory would embolden Iran, North Korea and China.

That matters for Europe‚Äôs security.
And it matters for America‚Äôs security.

So supporting Ukraine serves U.S. interests.

For a tiny fraction of annual defence spending, the United States has helped Ukraine destroy a major part of Russia‚Äôs combat capacity.  
Without placing a single American soldier in harm‚Äôs way.   

I welcome the clear commitment from President Biden and you.
To sustain U.S. support to Ukraine.
And to work with Congress to achieve that.

As you said, other Allies are also stepping up.

In fact, what European NATO Allies and Canada provide ‚Äì
in terms of military, financial, and humanitarian aid ‚Äì
actually exceeds what the U.S. is providing.

So truly joint effort from both sides of the Atlantic.

And I am confident that all NATO Allies will continue to deliver.
Because supporting Ukraine is not charity.
It is an investment in our own security. 

President Putin started this war, and he could end it today ‚Äì if he stopped attacking a neighbour.
The war could also end if Ukraine stopped defending itself,
But that would not mean peace.
It would mean Russian occupation.
And occupation is not peace.

A just peace will require President Putin to realise that he will not get what he wants on the battlefield.
Moscow must accept a negotiated solution where Ukraine prevails as a sovereign, independent nation.

What happens around the negotiating table is inextricably linked to the situation on the battlefield.
So if we want a lasting, just peace, we must provide Ukraine with more weapons and ammunition.
Weapons to Ukraine is the path to peace.

Finally, we also discussed adapting our Alliance for the future.

In July, we will mark NATO‚Äôs 75th anniversary with a Summit here in Washington.

And as you said, NATO is getting stronger and bigger. 
Finland is already a member, Sweden will become a member soon. 
And this demonstrates that Putin is getting exactly the opposite of what he wanted.

He wanted less NATO, a weaker NATO.
He‚Äôs getting a stronger NATO and a more united NATO and a NATO with more members.

At the Summit, we will take further steps to bolster NATO‚Äôs strength.
Invest more in our defence.
And work with partners around the world.

Through NATO, the U.S. has more friends and allies than any other power.
Together, we make up 50 percent of the world‚Äôs economic and military might.

China and Russia have nothing like NATO.
It is why they always try to undermine our unity.

In times of growing competition and rivalry.
NATO makes the U.S. stronger and safer.
And all of us more secure.

Secretary Blinken, dear Tony,
Thank you again for your personal commitment to our transatlantic bond and to our shared security.

Thank you.

recommandationVideos.Title: Inside Rural Russia: When Military and Patriotism Are Your Life | ENDEVR Documentary
recommandationVideos.Description:
Inside Rural Russia: When Military and Patriotism Are Your Life | Town of Glory | ENDEVR Documentary

Watch 'The Oligarch's Wife - Married to a Hunted Russian Billionaire' here: https://youtu.be/QCJpX2nhY3Q

A heroic Soviet past and a destitute post-industrial present make the provincial town of Yenya susceptible to the Kremlin's aggressive anti-Western propaganda leading to the militarization of society from kindergarten to pension age. With few exceptions, Yelnyans raise their children to become good patriots. They don‚Äôt mind the eerie, all-encompassing militarization of society.

Filmed over the course of three years, this film introduces Western viewers to the small and prototypical provincial Russian town of Yelnya where people admire Vladimir Putin for making Russia great again. Yelnya has remained economically marginalized ever since the Soviet Union collapsed. But people have regained pride. They believe that President Putin is bringing back glory and power to the Russian nation. Not many object to the constant propaganda claims that fascism is threatening once again from the US and Europe and that Russia must stand ready to defend itself.

recommandationVideos.Title: Why French farmers are protesting in Paris: 'Jeremy Clarkson's right'
recommandationVideos.Description:
A tractor blockade established at eight points around Paris is intended to ‚Äústarve Parisians‚Äù, a French farmer has claimed.

Benoit Durand, a grain farmer, told French broadcaster BFM TV: ‚ÄúWe are holding a siege in Chartres, one hour away from Paris. It‚Äôs part of the blockade... the goal is to put pressure on the government.‚Äù

‚Äù[Blockading Paris] will happen naturally. Parisians are going to be hungry. The goal is to starve Parisians. That‚Äôs it‚Äù.

Around 800 tractors have surrounded the capital as farmers protest what they say are stringent environmental regulations, red tape and low pay.

Near Beauvais, north of Paris, dozens of tractors lined the highway in one of many such protests across the country, displaying banners that read:  ‚ÄúOur end will be your hunger‚Äù ‚Äì a play on the similar-sounding French words fin (end) and faim (hunger).

Armoured police vehicles were deployed to Rungis on Monday after some farmers threatened to ‚Äúoccupy‚Äù it. Over 8,000 tons of goods pass through its market every day to feed nearly 12 million people.

In the event of major disruption, Paris would only have three days‚Äô food supplies, as deliveries are made every day, according to government agency Ademe.

recommandationVideos.Description:
With the Russo-Ukrainian war about to enter its third year, much of the wider conflict has ground down to long-range strikes and skirmishes, with the manpower and armour required to carry large scale offensives currently depleted. Ukraine is still attempting to recapture its lost territory but has made only marginal gains.

Instead, it has ramped up drone and missile strikes on Russia itself, with much of this forward strategy occurring near the city of Belgorod, which is just a 2 hour drive from Kharkiv.

The reason is simple - let the Russian population know that there is still a war going on on their doorstep.

recommandationVideos.Title: NATO Secretary General with the üá∫üá∏ US Secretary of State Antony J. Blinken, 29 JAN 2024
recommandationVideos.Description:
Joint press conference by the NATO Secretary General, Jens Stoltenberg and the US Secretary of State,  Antony J. Blinken, 29 January 2024.

üó£ | NATO Secretary General:

Thanks so much, Secretary Blinken, dear Tony,
Thank you for hosting me here in Washington.

It is always good to meet with you.
And even more important given the dangers we face.

So let me begin by offering my deepest condolences for the US troops killed and wounded in yesterday‚Äôs drone attack in Jordan.

We see Iran continue to destabilise the region.

Iran also bears responsibility for backing terrorists who attack our ships in the Red Sea.

Tehran‚Äôs behaviour reminds us of what a world without rules looks like:
Unpredictable and dangerous.
A world where our security becomes more expensive.

I welcome your tireless diplomacy, Secretary Blinken, to prevent further escalation of the war in Gaza. 
Your efforts to alleviate human suffering.
And your hard work toward a peaceful resolution.

Russia‚Äôs brutal war against Ukraine is nearing the two-year mark.
And a Russian victory would embolden Iran, North Korea and China.

That matters for Europe‚Äôs security.
And it matters for America‚Äôs security.

So supporting Ukraine serves U.S. interests.

For a tiny fraction of annual defence spending, the United States has helped Ukraine destroy a major part of Russia‚Äôs combat capacity.  
Without placing a single American soldier in harm‚Äôs way.   

I welcome the clear commitment from President Biden and you.
To sustain U.S. support to Ukraine.
And to work with Congress to achieve that.

As you said, other Allies are also stepping up.

In fact, what European NATO Allies and Canada provide ‚Äì
in terms of military, financial, and humanitarian aid ‚Äì
actually exceeds what the U.S. is providing.

So truly joint effort from both sides of the Atlantic.

And I am confident that all NATO Allies will continue to deliver.
Because supporting Ukraine is not charity.
It is an investment in our own security. 

President Putin started this war, and he could end it today ‚Äì if he stopped attacking a neighbour.
The war could also end if Ukraine stopped defending itself,
But that would not mean peace.
It would mean Russian occupation.
And occupation is not peace.

A just peace will require President Putin to realise that he will not get what he wants on the battlefield.
Moscow must accept a negotiated solution where Ukraine prevails as a sovereign, independent nation.

What happens around the negotiating table is inextricably linked to the situation on the battlefield.
So if we want a lasting, just peace, we must provide Ukraine with more weapons and ammunition.
Weapons to Ukraine is the path to peace.

Finally, we also discussed adapting our Alliance for the future.

In July, we will mark NATO‚Äôs 75th anniversary with a Summit here in Washington.

And as you said, NATO is getting stronger and bigger. 
Finland is already a member, Sweden will become a member soon. 
And this demonstrates that Putin is getting exactly the opposite of what he wanted.

He wanted less NATO, a weaker NATO.
He‚Äôs getting a stronger NATO and a more united NATO and a NATO with more members.

At the Summit, we will take further steps to bolster NATO‚Äôs strength.
Invest more in our defence.
And work with partners around the world.

Through NATO, the U.S. has more friends and allies than any other power.
Together, we make up 50 percent of the world‚Äôs economic and military might.

China and Russia have nothing like NATO.
It is why they always try to undermine our unity.

In times of growing competition and rivalry.
NATO makes the U.S. stronger and safer.
And all of us more secure.

Secretary Blinken, dear Tony,
Thank you again for your personal commitment to our transatlantic bond and to our shared security.

Thank you.

A heroic Soviet past and a destitute post-industrial present make the provincial town of Yenya susceptible to the Kremlin's aggressive anti-Western propaganda leading to the militarization of society from kindergarten to pension age. With few exceptions, Yelnyans raise their children to become good patriots. They don‚Äôt mind the eerie, all-encompassing militarization of society.

Filmed over the course of three years, this film introduces Western viewers to the small and prototypical provincial Russian town of Yelnya where people admire Vladimir Putin for making Russia great again. Yelnya has remained economically marginalized ever since the Soviet Union collapsed. But people have regained pride. They believe that President Putin is bringing back glory and power to the Russian nation. Not many object to the constant propaganda claims that fascism is threatening once again from the US and Europe and that Russia must stand ready to defend itself.

recommandationVideos.Title: Putin challenges West: "What right do you have to warn anyone?"
recommandationVideos.Description:
Russian President Vladimir Putin on Thursday accused the U.S. of 'arrogance' in telling other countries how to behave.

In his annual keynote speech at the Valdai Discussion Club, this year in Sochi, Putin addressed the United States. 

"All the time, we hear, 'You must', 'You have to', We're seriously warning you'. Who are you anyway? What right do you have to warn anyone? Maybe it‚Äôs time you yourself got rid of your arrogance and stopped behaving that way towards the world."

Putin said Russia saw all civilizations as equal and was ready for "constructive cooperation" while the West, which he accused of having forgotten the meaning of compromise and seeing any country that opposed it as an enemy. 

Putin also suggested that the plane crash that killed Wagner mercenary chief Yevgeny Prigozhin in August was caused by hand grenades detonating inside the aircraft, not by a missile attack.

The private Embraer jet on which Prigozhin was travelling to St. Petersburg crashed north of Moscow on Aug. 23, killing all 10 people on board.

DISCLAIMER FOR GENERAL STAFF LOSSES DATA
1) These are real people with real lives and real families who love them. Don‚Äôt let the numbers sap your humanity.
2) These numbers probably aren‚Äôt accurate but they‚Äôre the best we have and we don‚Äôt need them to be accurate to be indicative of patterns of activity. 
3) All losses are estimates.  Losses cannot be counted with accuracy because of the conditions on the ground. 
4) Both sides would see it to be of their advantage to minimize their own losses maximize the other side‚Äôs losses. 
5) Neither side releases their losses but we have enough transparency from the Ukrainian side to have confidence in they are indicative.
6) Personnel losses are hard to count. If a soldier gets injured, heals up, and returns to the front line only to get injured again, is that one loss or two? Also, how to deal with losses from PMC‚Äôs or soldiers fighting with RF from occupied territories? 
7) Equipment losses are hard to count. If an AA complex involves several parts and one part gets disabled, is that a loss, or a fraction of a loss? If a tank gets disabled, repaired, back into the fight, then disabled again, is that one lost tank or two?
8) All recorded losses are vulnerable to multiple reporting. We have already seen numerous cases of multiple drones in the air reporting the same loss from different angles as multiple engagements. 
9) Losses are not always reported on the same day they occurred. It is frequent that drone losses are reported at least 24 hours after other terrestrial equipment losses. Certain losses may not be reported for days or weeks for military intelligence reasons.

DISCLAIMER FOR GENERAL STAFF LOSSES DATA
1) These are real people with real lives and real families who love them. Don‚Äôt let the numbers sap your humanity.
2) These numbers probably aren‚Äôt accurate but they‚Äôre the best we have and we don‚Äôt need them to be accurate to be indicative of patterns of activity. 
3) All losses are estimates.  Losses cannot be counted with accuracy because of the conditions on the ground. 
4) Both sides would see it to be of their advantage to minimize their own losses maximize the other side‚Äôs losses. 
5) Neither side releases their losses but we have enough transparency from the Ukrainian side to have confidence in they are indicative.
6) Personnel losses are hard to count. If a soldier gets injured, heals up, and returns to the front line only to get injured again, is that one loss or two? Also, how to deal with losses from PMC‚Äôs or soldiers fighting with RF from occupied territories? 
7) Equipment losses are hard to count. If an AA complex involves several parts and one part gets disabled, is that a loss, or a fraction of a loss? If a tank gets disabled, repaired, back into the fight, then disabled again, is that one lost tank or two?
8) All recorded losses are vulnerable to multiple reporting. We have already seen numerous cases of multiple drones in the air reporting the same loss from different angles as multiple engagements. 
9) Losses are not always reported on the same day they occurred. It is frequent that drone losses are reported at least 24 hours after other terrestrial equipment losses. Certain losses may not be reported for days or weeks for military intelligence reasons.

recommandationVideos.Description:
Joint press conference by the NATO Secretary General, Jens Stoltenberg and the US Secretary of State,  Antony J. Blinken, 29 January 2024.

üó£ | NATO Secretary General:

Thanks so much, Secretary Blinken, dear Tony,
Thank you for hosting me here in Washington.

It is always good to meet with you.
And even more important given the dangers we face.

So let me begin by offering my deepest condolences for the US troops killed and wounded in yesterday‚Äôs drone attack in Jordan.

We see Iran continue to destabilise the region.

Iran also bears responsibility for backing terrorists who attack our ships in the Red Sea.

Tehran‚Äôs behaviour reminds us of what a world without rules looks like:
Unpredictable and dangerous.
A world where our security becomes more expensive.

I welcome your tireless diplomacy, Secretary Blinken, to prevent further escalation of the war in Gaza. 
Your efforts to alleviate human suffering.
And your hard work toward a peaceful resolution.

Russia‚Äôs brutal war against Ukraine is nearing the two-year mark.
And a Russian victory would embolden Iran, North Korea and China.

That matters for Europe‚Äôs security.
And it matters for America‚Äôs security.

So supporting Ukraine serves U.S. interests.

For a tiny fraction of annual defence spending, the United States has helped Ukraine destroy a major part of Russia‚Äôs combat capacity.  
Without placing a single American soldier in harm‚Äôs way.   

I welcome the clear commitment from President Biden and you.
To sustain U.S. support to Ukraine.
And to work with Congress to achieve that.

As you said, other Allies are also stepping up.

In fact, what European NATO Allies and Canada provide ‚Äì
in terms of military, financial, and humanitarian aid ‚Äì
actually exceeds what the U.S. is providing.

So truly joint effort from both sides of the Atlantic.

And I am confident that all NATO Allies will continue to deliver.
Because supporting Ukraine is not charity.
It is an investment in our own security. 

President Putin started this war, and he could end it today ‚Äì if he stopped attacking a neighbour.
The war could also end if Ukraine stopped defending itself,
But that would not mean peace.
It would mean Russian occupation.
And occupation is not peace.

A just peace will require President Putin to realise that he will not get what he wants on the battlefield.
Moscow must accept a negotiated solution where Ukraine prevails as a sovereign, independent nation.

What happens around the negotiating table is inextricably linked to the situation on the battlefield.
So if we want a lasting, just peace, we must provide Ukraine with more weapons and ammunition.
Weapons to Ukraine is the path to peace.

Finally, we also discussed adapting our Alliance for the future.

In July, we will mark NATO‚Äôs 75th anniversary with a Summit here in Washington.

And as you said, NATO is getting stronger and bigger. 
Finland is already a member, Sweden will become a member soon. 
And this demonstrates that Putin is getting exactly the opposite of what he wanted.

He wanted less NATO, a weaker NATO.
He‚Äôs getting a stronger NATO and a more united NATO and a NATO with more members.

At the Summit, we will take further steps to bolster NATO‚Äôs strength.
Invest more in our defence.
And work with partners around the world.

Through NATO, the U.S. has more friends and allies than any other power.
Together, we make up 50 percent of the world‚Äôs economic and military might.

China and Russia have nothing like NATO.
It is why they always try to undermine our unity.

In times of growing competition and rivalry.
NATO makes the U.S. stronger and safer.
And all of us more secure.

Secretary Blinken, dear Tony,
Thank you again for your personal commitment to our transatlantic bond and to our shared security.

Thank you.

recommandationVideos.Description:

Soldiers of the Special Operations Forces of Ukraine discovered and destroyed two strongholds of the Russian occupiers in the Zaporizhzhia direction, according to the Special Operations Forces.
Reportedly, operators of one of the Special Operations Forces units, while conducting reconnaissance in the Zaporizhzhia direction, discovered two enemy strongholds, the destruction of which was necessary to improve the tactical situation.
The enemy targets were struck by strike aircraft. As a result of accurate work, the strongholds, along with heavy equipment and enemy personnel, were destroyed.
"Finally, to remind the occupiers once again that this is Ukrainian land and they are not here for long, the operators used a drone to plant a blue and yellow flag in place of the destroyed enemy strongholds," the Special Operations Forces adds.
Recently, the Special Operations Forces of the Armed Forces of Ukraine destroyed Russian observation posts and killed five Russians in Kherson Oblast.
It is noted that while conducting special reconnaissance on the southern front, the operators of the 73rd Naval Centre of the Special Operations Forces notice Russian observation posts and personnel.
To kill Russians, the UAV crew inflicted fire damage on the targets using a thermal imaging drone with a discharge system. After that, the Special Operations Forces combat group moved out for the mop-up operation of observation posts.
"Despite heavy enemy artillery fire, the operators came close to the enemy, took favourable positions and began direct actions.
As a result of the professional work of Special Operations Forces soldiers, enemy observation posts were destroyed, and five enemy servicemen were killed. In the future, this will allow us to control more sections on this front", Special Operations Forces added.

resultVideos.Title: Ukraine 'blows up Russian Black Sea oil terminal'
resultVideos.Description:
A Russian oil terminal on the Black Sea has been blown up in an apparent Ukrainian drone strike.

Video footage from the scene showed a drone flying towards the Tuapse oil depot in Russia‚Äôs Krasnodar region on Wednesday night.

City mayor Sergey Boyko said there were no casualties and the fire was extinguished at 4.53am local time (1.53am GMT).

The prominent Baza Telegram channel said explosions were heard in the city before the fire started at the Rosneft depot as anti-air defences attempted to engage the drone.

Ukraine is yet to officially claim responsibility.

It has attacked four other oil depots in Russia this month, including one in St Petersburg more than 700 miles from Ukraine‚Äôs northern border.

recommandationVideos.Title: Why French farmers are protesting in Paris: 'Jeremy Clarkson's right'
recommandationVideos.Description:
A tractor blockade established at eight points around Paris is intended to ‚Äústarve Parisians‚Äù, a French farmer has claimed.

Benoit Durand, a grain farmer, told French broadcaster BFM TV: ‚ÄúWe are holding a siege in Chartres, one hour away from Paris. It‚Äôs part of the blockade... the goal is to put pressure on the government.‚Äù

‚Äù[Blockading Paris] will happen naturally. Parisians are going to be hungry. The goal is to starve Parisians. That‚Äôs it‚Äù.

Around 800 tractors have surrounded the capital as farmers protest what they say are stringent environmental regulations, red tape and low pay.

Near Beauvais, north of Paris, dozens of tractors lined the highway in one of many such protests across the country, displaying banners that read:  ‚ÄúOur end will be your hunger‚Äù ‚Äì a play on the similar-sounding French words fin (end) and faim (hunger).

Armoured police vehicles were deployed to Rungis on Monday after some farmers threatened to ‚Äúoccupy‚Äù it. Over 8,000 tons of goods pass through its market every day to feed nearly 12 million people.

In the event of major disruption, Paris would only have three days‚Äô food supplies, as deliveries are made every day, according to government agency Ademe.

recommandationVideos.Title: Opposing fronts - Russia and Ukraine face off in the Belgorod region as war drags on | Analysis
recommandationVideos.Description:
With the Russo-Ukrainian war about to enter its third year, much of the wider conflict has ground down to long-range strikes and skirmishes, with the manpower and armour required to carry large scale offensives currently depleted. Ukraine is still attempting to recapture its lost territory but has made only marginal gains.

Instead, it has ramped up drone and missile strikes on Russia itself, with much of this forward strategy occurring near the city of Belgorod, which is just a 2 hour drive from Kharkiv.

The reason is simple - let the Russian population know that there is still a war going on on their doorstep.

Keywords: Repairing a Cylinder Barrel for BIG D11 Bulldozer
recommandationVideos.Description:
We‚Äôre about to inject some fresh steel into this cylinder barrel off a massive D11T bulldozer! This isn't your average DIY project. This cylinder barrel is part of a key hydraulic component off a Caterpillar D11T bulldozer blade, responsible for tilting the heavy chunk of blade forward and backwards and also tilting the blade left and right. Watch the power of machining as we disassemble the old damaged barrel before transforming a plain steel tube into the perfect new barrel courtesy of our trusty lathe. Then with the help of a trusty welding torch and a steady hand we‚Äôll weld the new barrel to the cylinder head flange before using our Sunnen horizontal honing machine to hone the new barrel to precision spec. We continue the job by fitting, aligning and tacking the barrel end to the newly honed barrel before some more flawless welding to complete the repair!

In this video we are using: 
- Hafco TM-26120G Centre Lathe
 - WIA 500i Weldmatic welder 
- Sunnen HTA-4100 Horizontal hone

recommandationVideos.Description:
The International Court of Justice has delivered its interim judgment. Even a political body appointed by the United Nations General Assembly, whose members are mainly non-democratic states, couldn‚Äôt bring itself to order Israel to ceasefire, but we should not be grateful for that. They had no moral right to order Israel to cease its just war of self-defense in the first place.

What these so-called judges should have done is express the gratitude of the international community of civilized nations for the bravery and sacrifice of Israel‚Äôs young soldiers, who are going door to door to fight war to defeat the forces of barbarism in the Middle East, so that many of you listening to this, who live in the free world will not one have to do it yourselves in your own cities to protect your own children and grandchildren.
 
This is not 1938. It is 2024 and the Jewish people do not have to go on our knees to beg for the right to defend ourselves against those who seek to exterminate us. 

#israel #icj #gaza
